tine's in Canterbury. The monks collected texts that provided positive justifications for the practice of magic and books in which works of magic were copied side by side with works of more licit genres. In Magic in the Cloister, Sophie Page uses this collection to explore the gradual shift toward more positive attitudes to magical texts and ideas in medieval Europe. She examines what attracted monks to magic texts, works, and how they combined magic with their intellectual interests and monastic life. By showing how it was possible for religious insiders to integrate magical studies with their orthodox worldview, Magic in the Cloister contributes to a broader understanding of the role of magical texts and ideas and their acceptance in the late Middle Ages.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aMagicxManuscriptsxHistory. 0aMagicxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aMagiczEnglandzCanterburyxHistory. 0aManuscripts, Medieval. 7aRELIGION / History.2bisacsh  aMagic St. Augustine’s Abbey Canterbury Magic in History Series Benedictine Byzantium Sicily Spain twelfth century thirteenth century Renaissance natural magic Arabic image magic Ritual Magic Liber vaccae Liber de essentia spirituum Ars notoria Glossulae super Librum imaginum lunae Liber de essentia spirituum.  aSophie Page.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271060965?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271060965423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271060965/original  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  a